# SynthPress Architecture

## Monorepo

- **pnpm workspaces** with **Turborepo**. Primary app lives at `apps/web/` (Next.js 16).
- Path alias: `@/` maps to `apps/web/src/`.
- Run scripts via Turbo from root (`pnpm dev`, `pnpm test`) or directly in `apps/web/`.

## Component Architecture (Atomic Design)

All UI components live in `apps/web/src/components/` under four layers. Each component gets its own folder with co-located files:

```
components/
  foundations/          # Design token documentation (stories only, no components)
  atoms/Name/           # Smallest building blocks (Button, Input, Badge, etc.)
    Name.tsx            # Component implementation (dumb, stateless, no data fetching)
    Name.test.tsx       # Vitest + React Testing Library tests
    Name.stories.tsx    # Storybook CSF3 story
    index.ts            # Barrel: re-exports component + types
  molecules/Name/       # Compositions of atoms (Navbar, FeatureCard, PricingCard)
  organisms/Name/       # Page sections composed of molecules/atoms (Hero, Pricing, Footer)
  templates/Name/       # Page layouts that compose organisms (LandingLayout)
```

Layer barrel files (`atoms/index.ts`, `molecules/index.ts`, etc.) re-export all components and their types.

## Component Rules

- **All components are dumb/presentational.** No data fetching, no hooks that call APIs, no server imports.
- **Props include `className?: string`** for composability. Merge with `cn()` from `@/lib/cn`.
- **Named exports only.** `export function Button(...)` — never default exports.
- **Variant patterns:** Define `const variantStyles = { ... } as const` and export `type ButtonVariant = keyof typeof variantStyles`.
- **Every new component MUST have:** `Name.tsx`, `index.ts`, `Name.test.tsx`, and `Name.stories.tsx`.

## Data Flow Architecture

```
Page (Server Component)
  ├─ Option A: Fetch data server-side → pass as props to dumb component
  └─ Option B: Render a Connector for interactive features
       └─ Connector ("use client", calls controller hook)
            └─ Controller hook (calls server actions for mutations, manages state)
                 ├─ Uses smaller utility hooks for reusable logic
                 └─ Calls server actions (NEVER Supabase directly)
                      └─ Server action → Service (optional) → Supabase
```

### Server Actions (the ONLY way to talk to Supabase)

Client code NEVER imports Supabase. All backend interactions go through server actions.

- **Location:** Route-group action files (`(auth)/actions.ts`, `(dashboard)/actions.ts`) or `src/actions/` for shared actions.
- **Pattern:** `"use server"` → validate input → create server Supabase client → perform operation → return `{ data, error }`.
- **Rule:** Server actions are thin wrappers. Extract complex multi-step logic into services.

### Services (`src/services/`)

Reusable backend logic that multiple server actions or route handlers might need.

- Pure functions that receive a Supabase client or create their own.
- Handle complex multi-step operations, cross-table logic, or business rules.
- Naming: `project-service.ts`, `article-service.ts`, `billing-service.ts`.
- **Every service file starts with `import "server-only";`** so any client-side
  import fails at build time. See `nextjs-supabase` rule for the full list.
- Race-prone read-then-write logic (counters, balances) goes through a
  Postgres `security definer` RPC, not separate JS queries. See
  `supabase-database` rule for the atomic RPC pattern.

```ts
// src/services/project-service.ts
import "server-only";
import { createClient } from "@/lib/supabase/server";

export async function createProjectWithDefaults(name: string, userId: string) {
  const supabase = await createClient();
  const { data: project } = await supabase.from("projects").insert({ name, owner_id: userId }).select().single();
  // create default settings, add initial content, etc.
  return project;
}
```

### Connector Components (`src/connectors/`)

Thin `"use client"` wrappers that bridge server data into interactive client components.

- Call a controller hook.
- Pass hook results as props to a dumb component.
- Accept `initialData` from a Server Component parent.
- No business logic — just the glue.

```tsx
// src/connectors/ProjectListConnector.tsx
"use client";
import { useProjectList } from "@/hooks/useProjectList";
import { ProjectList } from "@/components/organisms/ProjectList";

export function ProjectListConnector({ initialProjects }: { initialProjects: Project[] }) {
  const props = useProjectList(initialProjects);
  return <ProjectList {...props} />;
}
```

### Controller Hooks (`src/hooks/use[Feature].ts`)

One controller hook per feature/page section. Encapsulates all client-side logic for that feature.

- Named after the feature: `useProjectList`, `useArticleEditor`, `useOnboarding`.
- Returns a props-shaped object that a dumb component can spread.
- Calls **server actions** for mutations (never Supabase).
- Manages local UI state (loading, optimistic updates, form state).
- Composes smaller utility hooks for shared logic.

```tsx
// src/hooks/useProjectList.ts
"use client";
import { useState, useTransition } from "react";
import { deleteProject } from "@/actions/projects";
import { useOptimisticList } from "@/hooks/useOptimisticList";

export function useProjectList(initialProjects: Project[]) {
  const [isPending, startTransition] = useTransition();
  const { items, removeItem } = useOptimisticList(initialProjects);

  function handleDelete(id: string) {
    startTransition(async () => {
      removeItem(id);
      await deleteProject(id);
    });
  }

  return { projects: items, onDelete: handleDelete, isLoading: isPending };
}
```

### Utility Hooks (`src/hooks/use[Capability].ts`)

Small, reusable hooks that controller hooks compose. Each does one thing well.

- `useOptimisticList` — optimistic add/remove/reorder for any list
- `useFormState` — form field state + validation + submission
- `useDebounce` — debounced values
- `useMediaQuery` — responsive breakpoint detection

These hooks never call server actions or Supabase. They manage pure client-side logic.

## State Management

- **Zustand** for client-side UI state (`src/stores/`). Typed interfaces, `create<State>()`.
- Prefer server state (Supabase queries in Server Components / server actions) over client state.
- Auth state comes from the server (middleware + Server Component `getUser()` checks). No client-side auth store needed.

## Styling

- **Tailwind CSS v4** configured via `globals.css` with `@theme inline` — no `tailwind.config.js`.
- Design tokens are CSS custom properties (`--sp-*`). Use semantic Tailwind classes (`bg-surface`, `text-foreground`, `border-border`).
- Brand gradients: `bg-gradient-accent`, `bg-gradient-brand`, `text-gradient-accent`.
- Border radius via CSS vars: `rounded-[var(--sp-radius-lg)]`.
- `cn()` is a zero-dependency class joiner — NOT `clsx`/`tailwind-merge`.

## Testing Requirements

- **Every component** gets a co-located `Name.test.tsx` (Vitest + React Testing Library).
- **Every component** gets a co-located `Name.stories.tsx` (Storybook CSF3).
- **Controller hooks** get `useFeature.test.ts` files — mock server actions, test state transitions.
- **Server actions** get `actions.test.ts` files — mock Supabase client, test validation and error paths.
- **E2E tests** in `apps/web/e2e/` (Playwright) — test critical user flows end-to-end.
- Coverage targets: 100% for `src/components/`, `src/lib/`, `src/hooks/`, `src/services/`, `src/connectors/`, `src/stores/`, `src/actions/`.

## Directory Overview

```
apps/web/src/
  app/                   # Next.js App Router pages, layouts, route handlers, server actions
  components/            # Dumb UI components (atomic design layers)
  connectors/            # "use client" wrappers that connect hooks to components
  hooks/                 # Controller hooks + utility hooks
  actions/               # Shared server actions (domain-specific)
  services/              # Reusable backend logic
  stores/                # Zustand stores (client UI state only)
  lib/                   # Utilities (cn, supabase clients, etc.)
```
